                <td><strong>Traditional SEO</strong></td>
                <td>Google, Bing</td>
                <td>Links, E-E-A-T, Core Web Vitals</td>
                <td>Always first</td>
              </tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Generative Engine Optimization (GEO)</strong></td><td>ChatGPT, Perplexity, Gemini</td><td>Structured answers, cited sources, schema</td><td>High — fast growth</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Social search</strong></td><td>TikTok, Instagram, YouTube, LinkedIn</td><td>Engagement, native format, recency</td><td>High for B2C/Gen Z</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Community search</strong></td><td>Reddit, Quora, niche forums</td><td>Helpfulness, authenticity, upvotes</td><td>Medium</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Voice search</strong></td><td>Siri, Alexa, Google Assistant</td><td>Conversational phrasing, local signals</td><td>Medium for local</td></tr>
              <tr><td><strong>Marketplace search</strong></td><td>Amazon, Etsy, Shopify</td><td>Reviews, listing completeness, conversion rate</td><td>High for e-commerce</td></tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real search everywhere optimization examples</h2>

        <h3>Plumbing company — full discovery coverage</h3>
        <p>A plumbing company publishes 30 blog posts per month for Google rankings. Their team posts short-form video tips on TikTok and Instagram Reels showing common pipe fixes. They monitor and respond to Reddit threads about plumbing issues in their city. When a homeowner searches "emergency plumber" on any platform, this company appears. Result: 3x more inbound contacts than competitors running Google-only campaigns.</p>

        <h3>SaaS company — AI visibility gap</h3>
        <p>A project management software company ranks well for target keywords in traditional search. But when prospects ask ChatGPT "best project management tools for agencies," they do not appear. When buyers search YouTube for software reviews, no videos come up. They capture Google traffic but miss the AI and video discovery channels that increasingly influence B2B purchase decisions.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Search everywhere optimization vs traditional SEO — which to use</h2>
        <p>They are not alternatives — one extends the other. But resource allocation decisions are real.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Traditional SEO (Google-first)</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Lower resource requirement — one platform, one set of signals</li>
              <li>Measurable with standard rank tracking tools</li>
              <li>Still drives the majority of organic traffic for most businesses</li>
              <li>Foundational — other channels often credit Google authority</li>
              <li>Best starting point for any business</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Search everywhere optimization</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Captures growing share of queries leaving Google</li>
              <li>Required for brands targeting Gen Z and AI-first users</li>
              <li>Builds brand visibility that rank trackers cannot measure</li>
              <li>Multi-format content requirement increases production cost</li>
              <li>Best after Google fundamentals are stable</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">5 best practices for search everywhere optimization</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Start with Google and AI, then expand.</strong> Establish organic search fundamentals first. A well-structured, authoritative site performs better across all platforms because it builds the credibility signals that AI and social algorithms also reward.</li>
          <li><strong>Repurpose content systematically, not randomly.</strong> A pillar blog post can become a YouTube explainer, a TikTok series, a Reddit AMA, and a ChatGPT-cited FAQ page. Build repurposing into your content workflow — not as an afterthought.</li>
          <li><strong>Match format to platform algorithm.</strong> YouTube rewards watch time and structured chapters. TikTok rewards hook-heavy short video. Reddit rewards genuine helpfulness. Optimizing for engagement signals on each platform drives discovery, not just reach.</li>
          <li><strong>Track share of voice per channel.</strong> Rank tracking covers Google. Add AI mention monitoring (ask ChatGPT about your category weekly), YouTube view counts on relevant queries, and Reddit mention tracking to your measurement stack.</li>
          <li><strong>Audit competitors' multi-platform presence.</strong> Where do your top competitors appear that you do not? Platform gaps are opportunity gaps. A competitor who appears in AI answers, on YouTube, and in Reddit discussions for your target topics has a multi-channel moat you need a deliberate strategy to close.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — social-first without Google</div>
          <p>Some brands go all-in on TikTok and Instagram search visibility while neglecting Google. The result: excellent social search performance with zero organic traffic. Social search intent is often discovery-stage; Google captures purchase-stage intent. You need both. Always establish Google foundations before expanding to other platforms.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common search everywhere optimization mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Treating it as one tactic</strong> — it is a framework requiring platform-specific strategies, not a single action item</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping platform-native content</strong> — cross-posting identical content to every platform performs poorly on all of them</li>
          <li><strong>Not measuring AI visibility</strong> — if you cannot track whether ChatGPT or Perplexity cite you, you cannot improve it</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring community platforms</strong> — Reddit and Quora influence Google rankings and AI training data; they deserve attention</li>
          <li><strong>Expanding too fast</strong> — weak presence on seven platforms is worse than strong presence on three; prioritize by audience fit</li>
          <li><strong>No content repurposing system</strong> — multi-platform presence requires operational efficiency or costs spiral quickly</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="faq">Frequently asked questions</h2>
